{
  "texts": [
    "As we saw in (§2.1), having this ability means being subject to certain rational norms.",
    "According with norms of consistency ensures that the same reasons will, all things being equal, explain the same actions across cases (reasons to avoid getting wet consistently motivate rational agents to seek means of doing so); according with norms of holism means that the whole range of reasons an agent is sensitive to are relevant to determining what she does and so are relevant for the purposes of rationalizing explanation.",
    "Of course, real-world agents do not perfectly meet these standards.",
    "People do not bring to bear all of the considerations to which they are sensitive on every opportunity for action they are faced with, and they routinely fail to act consistently on those that 1 3 are brought to bear (for an overview of the empirical literature on failures of practical rationality, see Carrigan & Barkus, 2016).",
    "So, real-world agents at best approximate the norms of practical rationality."
  ]
}